Static method reference in an anonymous class Consider the following contrived &quot;hello, world&quot;:
```
abstract public class Main implements java.util.function.Supplier&lt;Runnable&gt; {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new Main() {
            private void hello() {
                System.out.println(&quot;hello, world&quot;);
            }
            @Override
            public Runnable get() {
                return this::hello;
            }
        }.get().run();
    }
}
```
This works. Now, imagine I realize that the `hello` method can be made `static`, how do I now get the reference to that method? Static method reference require to use the name of the class, which by definition is not there. I tried just trying to refer to `hello` or `::hello` or `null::hello` but these are not acceptable for the compiler.

Since the method is static, this can of course be easily worked around by putting the static method in the `Main` class and referring to it as `Main::hello`, but in a more complex setup the advantage of being able to refer to the static method would be restricting the static method to the smallest possible context. A case can be made of course that probably at that point you are probably abusing the ability to have anonymous classes, but my question mostly comes from curiosity to understand whether referring to static methods of anonymous classes is possible at all.

llmanswer:
In Java, it is not possible to directly reference a static method of an anonymous class. This is because anonymous classes do not have a name, and static methods require a class name to be referenced (e.g., `ClassName::methodName`).

### Why This Limitation Exists
1. **Anonymous Classes Lack a Name**: Since anonymous classes are unnamed, you cannot use a class name to refer to their static methods.
2. **Static Context**: Static methods are tied to the class itself, not an instance. Without a class name, there is no way to reference the static method.

### Workarounds
While you cannot directly reference a static method in an anonymous class, there are a few workarounds:

#### 1. **Move the Static Method to a Named Class**
As you mentioned, you can move the static method to the enclosing class (or another named class) and reference it using the class name. For example:
```java
abstract public class Main implements java.util.function.Supplier<Runnable> {
    private static void hello() {
        System.out.println("hello, world");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new Main() {
            @Override
            public Runnable get() {
                return Main::hello;
            }
        }.get().run();
    }
}
```

#### 2. **Use an Instance Method Instead**
If you want to keep the method within the anonymous class, you can make it an instance method (as in your original example). This avoids the need for a class name:
```java
abstract public class Main implements java.util.function.Supplier<Runnable> {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new Main() {
            private void hello() {
                System.out.println("hello, world");
            }

            @Override
            public Runnable get() {
                return this::hello;
            }
        }.get().run();
    }
}
```

#### 3. **Use a Static Block or Lambda**
If you want to keep the static method-like behavior but avoid moving it to a named class, you can use a static block or a lambda expression:
```java
abstract public class Main implements java.util.function.Supplier<Runnable> {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new Main() {
            private static final Runnable HELLO_RUNNABLE = () -> System.out.println("hello, world");

            @Override
            public Runnable get() {
                return HELLO_RUNNABLE;
            }
        }.get().run();
    }
}
```

#### 4. **Use a Nested Named Class**
If you want to restrict the static method to a smaller context, you can define a nested named class within the enclosing class:
```java
abstract public class Main implements java.util.function.Supplier<Runnable> {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        class Helper {
            static void hello() {
                System.out.println("hello, world");
            }
        }

        new Main() {
            @Override
            public Runnable get() {
                return Helper::hello;
            }
        }.get().run();
    }
}
```

### Conclusion
It is not possible to reference a static method of an anonymous class because anonymous classes lack a name. However, the workarounds above allow you to achieve similar functionality while adhering to Java's design constraints. If you find yourself needing static methods in an anonymous class, it might be a sign that the design should be refactored to use named classes or other constructs.

