---

### **Option 1: Use Wildcards**
If you don't need the method to return a specific type parameter, you can use wildcards (`?`) to indicate that the method can return any `AbstractClazz` with a type parameter that extends `Base`:

```java
AbstractClazz<? extends Base> method(boolean returnClass1) {
    if (returnClass1) {
        return new Clazz1();
    }
    return new Clazz2();
}
```

This tells the compiler that the method will return an `AbstractClazz` with some type that extends `Base`, but it doesn't specify exactly which type. This approach works if the caller doesn't need to know the exact type.

