#### 2. Create a Custom Serializer
The custom serializer will generate the exact JSON structure you need.

```java
import com.fasterxml.jackson.core.JsonGenerator;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.JsonSerializer;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.SerializerProvider;

import java.io.IOException;
import java.time.LocalDate;
import java.time.format.DateTimeFormatter;

public class CustomDateSerializer extends JsonSerializer<LocalDate> {
    private final DateTimeFormatter formatter = DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern("yyyy-MM-dd");

    @Override
    public void serialize(LocalDate value, JsonGenerator gen, SerializerProvider serializers) throws IOException {
        // Start writing the array
        gen.writeStartArray();

        // Write the "~#date" string
        gen.writeString("~#date");

        // Write the nested array with the formatted date
        gen.writeStartArray();
        gen.writeString(value.format(formatter));
        gen.writeEndArray();

        // End the array
        gen.writeEndArray();
    }
}
```

#### 3. Example Usage
Here’s how you can use the `MyDate` class and serialize it:

```java
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;

