How do I assign the derived class name as a param within the base class constructor? Let&#39;s assume I have a base class `Fruit`

```java
public class Fruit {

  String name;

  public Fruit(String name) {
    this.name = name
  }
}
```

And that I have class `Apple()` which extends `Fruit()` and I give that class two constructors.

```java
public class Apple extends Fruit {
	
    // constructor one
    public Apple() {
      this(&quot;Apple&quot;);
    }

    // constructor two
	public Apple(String name) {
		super(name);
	}
}
```

This lets me call `new Apple()` as well as `new Apple(&quot;Red Apple&quot;)`

Rather than having to add `constructor one` to each derived class of `Fruit`, I would prefer that `Fruit` resemble the following:

```java
public class Fruit {

  String name;

  // Automatically assign the classname from the derived class
  public Fruit() {
    this(this.getClass().getSimpleName());
  }

  public Fruit(String name) {
    this.name = name
  }
}
```

And then I could remove `constructor one` from `Apple` as it would be inheritted from `Fruit`

Ideally, this would let me call `new Apple()` and automatically set `Apple.name` to `Apple`

Unfortunately, `this(this.getClass().getSimpleName());` throws an error of

&gt; java cannot refer to &#39;this&#39; nor &#39;super&#39; while explicitly invoking a constructor

I use a similar pattern in other languages without any issues.  How do I assign the derived class name as a param within the base class constructor? Is something like this even possible in Java?

llmanswer:
In Java, the issue arises because you cannot call another constructor (`this(...)`) or the superclass constructor (`super(...)`) using `this` or `super` in the same constructor. This is a limitation of Java's constructor chaining mechanism. However, there are ways to achieve the desired behavior.

### Solution: Use a Static Helper Method
You can use a static helper method in the base class to determine the class name and pass it to the constructor. Here's how you can do it:

```java
public class Fruit {

    String name;

    // Default constructor that assigns the derived class name
    public Fruit() {
        this(getClassName());
    }

    // Constructor that accepts a name
    public Fruit(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    // Static helper method to get the derived class name
    private static String getClassName() {
        // Use the stack trace to determine the derived class name
        return new Throwable().getStackTrace()[2].getClassName();
    }
}
```

### Explanation:
1. The `getClassName()` method uses the stack trace to determine the name of the class that is calling the constructor. The `new Throwable().getStackTrace()` provides the stack trace, and `[2]` refers to the caller of the constructor (the derived class).
2. The default constructor `Fruit()` calls the `getClassName()` method to get the derived class name and passes it to the `Fruit(String name)` constructor.

### Example Usage:
```java
public class Apple extends Fruit {
    // No need to define any constructors here
}

public class Banana extends Fruit {
    // No need to define any constructors here
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Apple apple = new Apple();
        System.out.println(apple.name); // Output: Apple

        Banana banana = new Banana();
        System.out.println(banana.name); // Output: Banana
    }
}
```

### Caveats:
- The `getClassName()` method relies on the stack trace, which can be slightly slower than directly passing the class name. However, this is usually negligible unless you're creating a large number of objects in a performance-critical application.
- The derived class name will include the full package name (e.g., `com.example.Apple`). If you only want the simple class name, you can modify the `getClassName()` method to extract the simple name:
  ```java
  private static String getClassName() {
      String fullClassName = new Throwable().getStackTrace()[2].getClassName();
      return fullClassName.substring(fullClassName.lastIndexOf('.') + 1);
  }
  ```

### Alternative: Use Reflection in Derived Classes
If you don't want to rely on stack traces, you can use reflection in the derived class constructors to pass the class name explicitly:
```java
public class Apple extends Fruit {
    public Apple() {
        super(Apple.class.getSimpleName());
    }
}
```
This approach is more explicit but requires adding a constructor to each derived class.

### Conclusion:
Using the stack trace method in the base class is a clean and reusable solution that avoids the need to define constructors in each derived class. However, be mindful of its performance implications in scenarios where many objects are created frequently.

